Literature review

One of the most important topics for investors is understanding portfolio diversification. Having a diverse portfolio will make your investments less risky and more defensive during times of uncertainty. Harry Markowitz, the author of portfolio selection and the modern portfolio theory, states that when constructing portfolios, investors should maximize the portfolios return by (portfolio return formula) and minimize the variance by (add portfolio variance formula) of the portfolio to achieve favorable returns. However, in the Modern Portfolio Theory, Investors should seek the portfolio that reaches the maximum Sharpe ratio calculated by (add Sharpe ratio formula). This represents the greater risk of the portfolio investors should be compensated more.

Investment Data Analytics - Henry Bowers

Without any doubt having a strong understanding of fundamentals when it comes to stock picking is extremely important. What is also just as important is understanding data analytics for investment decision-making. Once an investor has decided which securities they want to include in their portfolio, depending on the risk levels their next step will be calculating the returns of the assets and the risk levels to determine the amount of asset allocation for their portfolio should have. Programming in R is amazingly beneficial for this because of the financial libraries. Such Libraries I will be discussing are the usefulness of Quantmod, Performance Analytics, Portfolio Analytics, and Tidyquant.

Quantmod - The quantmod package for R is designed to assist the quantitative trader in developing, testing, and deploying statistically based trading models. quantmod makes modeling easier by removing the repetitive workflow issues surrounding data management, modeling interfaces, and performance analysis.

Performance analytics - PerformanceAnalytics provides an R package of econometric functions for performance and risk analysis of financial instruments or portfolios. This package aims to aid practitioners and researchers in using the latest research for analysis of both normally and non-normally distributed return streams.

Portfolio Analytics - PortfolioAnalytics is an R package to provide numerical solutions for portfolio problems with complex constraints and objective sets. The goal of the package is to aid practitioners and researchers in solving portfolio optimization problems with complex constraints and objectives that mirror real-world applications.

Tidyquant - tidyquant integrates the best resources for collecting and analyzing financial data, zoo, xts, quantmod, and TTR, with the tidy data infrastructure of the tidyverse allowing for seamless interaction between each. You can now perform complete financial analyses in the tidyverse.

Portfolio Construction

As mentioned in the literature review, portfolio diversification is one of the most important factors in constructing a portfolio. Another important factor is testing the portfolio performance based on the asset allocations and calculating risk models for that portfolio. Depending on an investor, investment horizon if it is long, then the investor could take on more risk, if it is short, then they would be subjected to less risk. For years the typical asset allocations were 80/20, 80% equities 20% bonds if an investor wanted a more aggressive portfolio and if the investor was in their retirement stage, then the asset allocations would become 20/80, 20% equities, and 80% bonds. This asset allocation justifies the fact that bonds are seen as less risky compared to equity investments. However, the investment industry is changing. Crypto has entered the field and now that could be accounted for as well in asset allocations. Crypto is seen as a hedge for investors regarding a downfall in global currencies. Using R programming we can construct a portfolio of equities, crypto, bonds, and gold and test the performance against for example Ray Dalios All Weather Portfolio (AWP). The AWPs mission is to protect investors against inflation, deflation, lower than expected economic growth, and take advantage of an increase in economic growth. In accordance with Ray Dalio, the asset allocations for the AWP are 30% US stocks, 40% Long term treasuries, 15% Intermediate-term treasuries, 7.5% commodities, and 7.5% gold. As retail investors, we could replicate this by using the following ETFs. VTI, VGLT, VGIT, IAU and PDBC. Applying packages such as tidyquant, I will be able to retrieve asset price data, calculate returns, visualize the performance and calculate key performance metrics.

###############################################################################################
##                                The All Weather Portfolio                                 ##
###############################################################################################
AWP_tickers = c("VTI", "VGLT", "VGIT", "IAU", "PDBC")

AWP_weights = c(0.30, 0.40, 0.15, 0.08, 0.07)


# getting price data
AWP_price_data <- tq_get(AWP_tickers,
                   from = '2018-01-01',
                   to = '2022-04-01',
                   get = 'stock.prices')

# asset returns 
AWP_ret_data <- AWP_price_data %>%
  group_by(symbol) %>%
  tq_transmute(select = adjusted,
               mutate_fun = periodReturn,
               period = "daily",
               col_rename = "AWP_ret")


# AWP portfolio value returns 
AWP_Value <- AWP_ret_data %>%
  tq_portfolio(assets_col = symbol,
               returns_col = AWP_ret,
               weights = AWP_weights,
               col_rename = 'AWP_growth',
               wealth.index = TRUE, 
               rebalance = "years") %>%
  mutate(AWP_growth = AWP_growth * 1000)


plot_1 <- AWP_Value %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = date, y = AWP_growth)) +
  geom_line(size = 1, color = palette_light()[[1]]) +
  labs(title = "All Weather Portfolio",
       subtitle = "Ray Dalio portfolio",
       caption = "Data Source: Yahoo Finance",
       x = "", y = "Portfolio Value") +
  geom_smooth(method = "loess") +
  theme_classic() +
  scale_color_tq() +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::dollar)

As shown above, the AWP portfolio has proven to be a potentially worthwhile investment for investors. By just investing $1,000 into the portfolio in 2018, the investor would have gained nearly $400 to 500 dollars, however by investing into the portfolio with a mixture of equities, Bitcoin, gold, and bonds. The mixture portfolio would have seen nearly just over $1,000 in gains within the same period. Although the mixture portfolio is riskier compared to AWP. With the rise of bitcoin and other cryptocurrencies, there are a lot of speculations behind them, yet there is so much potential behind the crypto industry. We can now compare the cumulative returns of each portfolio to visualize which portfolio has achieved an overall greater return for an investment.

Thus, we can take note, that from 2018 until now, the mixed portfolio has achieved a larger return for its investment compared to investing in the All-Weather Portfolio. This is mainly because, in the past 5 years, bitcoin has increasingly become more popular amongst investors, driving more people to buy the coin since more people see the usefulness of a global universal currency.

Portfolio Optimization

Portfolio Optimization is a very intense ongoing challenge within the finance industry. Conducting an optimization, you can set many objectives or constraints for the optimization solver, Using the PortfolioAnalytics package in R we could create optimized portfolios within different types of solvers. In this example of optimization, I will be showcasing the random optimization solver. The random solver allows the analyst to create hundreds or even thousands of portfolios generated by the constraints and objectives. I will be taking the mixed portfolio constructed earlier and optimizing that and then back-test the performance of the optimization against the All-Weather Portfolio. constraints are used to make sure the portfolio allocations do not go above 100% and could be used to set a minimum or maximum of weight allocations and a target return for the portfolio. on the other hand, objectives are used to solve, for example, to maximize portfolio return, and minimize portfolio variance. hence the Minimum Variance Portfolio. We could go more in-depth than that by setting a risk budget for the portfolio by having a minimum and maximum portfolio risk based on the investors risk preference. Could even set an objective of the portfolio to minimize Value at risk and expected shortfall. Value at Risk in finance represents the percentage value the portfolio is at risk of losing, meanwhile expected shortfall based on historical performance could potentially tell how much the portfolio could lose in a short time frame.

Portfolio Backtesting

Back-testing portfolio optimization is used to test the performance of a strategy and to test how the portfolio performed against an underlying benchmark. Performing back-test gives visual and statistical evidence for investors to make informed investment decisions. The Following shows the backtest of the portfolio with a periodic rebalance of once a year. With the Portfolio Analytics package, you could rebalance portfolios on a yearly, daily, and quarterly basis. In this example since we will be a focus on a long-only portfolio, we will be rebalancing only once a year.

Mixed_tickers = c("VTI", "BTC-USD", "GLD")

# getting price data
Mixed_price_data <- tq_get(Mixed_tickers,
                   from = '2018-01-01',
                   to = '2022-04-01',
                   get = 'stock.prices')

# asset returns 
Mixed_ret_data <- Mixed_price_data %>%
  group_by(symbol) %>%
  tq_transmute(select = adjusted,
               mutate_fun = periodReturn,
               period = "daily",
               col_rename = "Mixed_ret",
               type = "log")


# turns data into an xts object 
Mixed_Port_xts <- Mixed_ret_data %>%
  spread(symbol, value = Mixed_ret) %>%
  tk_xts()


port_spec <- portfolio.spec(assets = colnames(Mixed_Port_xts))


port_spec <- add.constraint(portfolio = port_spec, type = "weight_Sum", min_sum = 0.99, max_sum = 1.01) # Weight sum constraint such that the weights sum to 1
port_spec <- add.constraint(portfolio = port_spec, type = "box", min = 0.15, max = 0.45) # box constraint, minimum and maximum allocations 



port_spec <- add.objective(portfolio = port_spec, type = "return", name = "mean") # Add an objective to maximize portfolio mean return
port_spec <- add.objective(portfolio = port_spec, type = "risk", name = "StdDev") # Add a risk objective to minimize portfolio standard deviation
port_spec <- add.objective(portfolio = port_spec, type = "risk_budget", name = "StdDev", min_prisk = 0.05, max_prisk = 0.10) # Add a risk budget objective
port_spec <- add.objective(portfolio= port_spec, type='risk', name='var') # Minimizing Value at risk
port_spec <- add.objective(portfolio=port_spec, type='risk', name='es') # minimizing Expected shortfall



rp <- random_portfolios(port_spec, 1000, "simplex")

opt_rebal <- optimize.portfolio.rebalancing(R = Mixed_Port_xts, portfolio = port_spec, 
                                            optimize_method = "random", rp = rp,
                                            trace = TRUE, rebalance_on = "years", training_period = 1, rolling_window = 10)
print(opt_rebal)

The portfolio back tests from the optimization have proven to be successful. The Mixed portfolio of just equities, bitcoin, and gold have outperformed the all-weather portfolio and the SP500 benchmark since 2019. In 2019, the AWP achieved an annualized return of 15%, a standard deviation of 21%, and a Sharpe ratio of 0.57. Meanwhile, the mixed Portfolio achieved an annualized return of 33%, a standard deviation of also 37% with a Sharpe ratio of 0.80. Theoretically based on the riskiness of the portfolio a rational investor would choose the higher Sharpe ratio portfolio, in this case, would be the mixed portfolio. Yet in most cases, the portfolio with a Sharpe ratio of 1 and above is the ideal situation for investors should choose from. When compared to the SP500 the All-weather portfolio has been recently underperforming the benchmark and makes investors wonder if it would be just better to invest in the SP500 or even take on a little more risk and add an alternative asset.

Portfolio Statistics

In statistics, we learned about linear regression models and their use of testing correlations between variables. For finance, a linear regression model is often used to calculate betas the slope and alpha the intercept. Beta is the measurement of systematic risk for the portfolio, if a portfolio has a beta of 1.02 then that represents every 1% move in the underlying benchmark, the portfolio either decreases or increases by 1.02%. This also represents that the closer the beta is to 1 the more correlated returns will be to the benchmark. Alpha on the other hand represents the amount an investment has outperformed or underperformed a benchmark. I will be using the SP500 as the benchmark to test portfolios correlations.

rets <- na.omit(cbind(Mixed_port_rets, AWP_port_rets))
